<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: MTA VOTES TO USE ITS 
OWN SECURITY FORCE FOR PATROLS, CITING SAVINGS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By HENRY CHU 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Metropolitan Transportation Authority on Wednesday selected its own 
security force to patrol the region's transit system instead of a joint squad 
of Los Angeles police officers and sheriff's deputies. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite an attempt by Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan to delay the decision, 
the MTA board of directors voted 11-2 to go with its in-house force, citing 
substantial cost savings for the cash-strapped agency. 
</P>
<P>
 Using the Los Angeles Police Department and the county Sheriff's Department 
would have cost $20 million more a year than using its own force, an 
unjustifiable expense for an agency grappling with a projected $126-million 
operating deficit, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 In the end, Riordan, who had voiced support for the police-sheriff's bid, 
sided with the majority after winning approval of an amendment to establish a 
multi-agency task force to monitor security services on the MTA's extensive 
network of bus and rail lines. 
</P>
<P>
 "I would hope and expect that this is going to start a process of . . . 
constant improvement," he said after the vote, which directors pushed to the 
top of their meeting agenda so that the mayor and others could attend the 
funeral of former President Richard Nixon. 
</P>
<P>
 Riordan said the task force would foster better collaboration between transit 
police, the LAPD and sheriff's deputies, and would reduce duplication of 
services. 
</P>
<P>
 MTA Police Chief Sharon K. Papa said she was pleased with the outcome: "To say 
we need to work cooperatively with the LAPD and the sheriff's is what I've said 
all along." 
</P>
<P>
 Her force is likely to jump from 300 officers to about 800 to fulfill its new 
mandate of patrolling all MTA buses, the Red Line subway, the aboveground Blue 
Line and the Green Line light-rail service due to open next year. 
</P>
<P>
 Currently, transit police oversee everything but the Blue Line, which is 
patrolled by sheriff's deputies. However, that contract expires June 30. Papa 
said negotiations will begin to transfer jurisdiction to her agency. HENRY CHU 
</P>
</TEXT>
