<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LOS ALAMITOS; CITY TO FORM POOL OF SERVICE CONSULTANTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 City officials are planning to form a pool of consultants that will provide 
specialized services for the Engineering and Public Services Department. 
</P>
<P>
 The consultants will provide design, planning, inspection and engineering 
services that often are too large, time consuming and complex, said Victor 
Rollinger, the city engineer and public works director. 
</P>
<P>
 Rollinger said the city administers up to $2 million a year in road repairs, 
traffic signal and storm drain improvements, bridge analysis and other city 
projects. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's more cost-effective to retain professional consultants on a contractual 
basis for the larger and more complex projects," Rollinger told the City 
Council on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 Rollinger said the city will invite engineering firms to apply as consultants 
next month and will make the selection in July. Contracts will be signed in 
August, he said, and the consultants will be called on a "as-needed" basis. 
</P>
<P>
 Last year, city officials decided to combine the jobs of city engineer and 
public works director -- after the retirement of Public Works Director Jerry 
Andersen -- to save money. 
</P>
<P>
 Rollinger was hired in January to serve as public works director and city 
engineer, although BSI Consultants of Santa Ana remained the city's consulting 
engineer. 
</P>
<P>
 The contract with BSI expires April 30 and will not be renewed because the 
city has its own engineer, officials said. BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</TEXT>
