<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY HALL JOURNAL: LA MIRADA; THEATER GROUP TO STOP FREE CAMPAIGN TICKETS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG MILLER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Whittier-La Mirada Musical Theatre Assn. will no longer give free tickets 
to political candidates, board members decided recently after learning that 
such contributions are improper. 
</P>
<P>
 The association gave six tickets worth $120 to the campaign of La Mirada City 
Councilman Wayne Rew, who was elected April 12 to his fifth term.The tickets, 
which had been requested by one of Rew's campaign workers, were used as a door 
prize at a campaign fund-raiser. 
</P>
<P>
 Tax-exempt groups such as the theatre association are not permitted to make 
political contributions, said Jim Shepherd, a spokesman for the state Franchise 
Tax Board. Shepherd said continued violation of the law could lead to removal 
of the association's tax-exempt status, but he added that "one incident would 
not typically jeopardize it." 
</P>
<P>
 "We were just totally oblivious to the fact that you couldn't do it," said 
Paul Garman, executive director of the association. "Obviously, we won't do it 
any longer." 
</P>
<P>
 The theater association organizes three musical productions each year at the 
La Mirada Theatre for the Performing Arts. Garman said the group receives as 
many as 30 requests a month for tickets. GREG MILLER 
</P>
</TEXT>
