<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: PARENTS TOLD: TEACH YOUR CHILDREN WELL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT SANDELL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Spending her Saturday in a classroom didn't sound like much fun to Jacqueline 
Thomas-Nelson of Lawndale. But the mother of four changed her mind when she 
heard it might make her a better parent. 
</P>
<P>
 Thomas-Nelson and about 50 others attended a day of free food, entertainment 
and parenting workshops at Leuzinger High School in Hawthorne. The discussions 
covered topics including prevention of teen-age pregnancy and resolution of 
family conflicts. 
</P>
<P>
 Speakers presented information in English, Spanish and Vietnamese but said the 
message of the seven-hour event was universal. 
</P>
<P>
 "Parents need to practice what they preach to their children," said Jackie 
LaBouff, a school psychologist who organized the Together We Can Family 
Celebration Fair. 
</P>
<P>
 "I wasn't going to come today, but then I thought about what that says to my 
kids," said Thomas-Nelson, 31, who has four sons ages 3 to 8. 
</P>
<P>
 But luring a large number of parents to the fair proved difficult. Organizers 
said they distributed thousands of flyers advertising Saturday's fair and ran a 
promotional video on local cable television. But just four dozen people 
attended. Last year, nearly 150 came. 
</P>
<P>
 LaBouff said some parents might not have received the flyers because they were 
given to students to take home. But she said apathy and denial also contributed 
to the low turnout. 
</P>
<P>
 The main thrust of the workshops was that parental behavior is the greatest 
influence on children's education. 
</P>
<P>
 "For example, we can't get youth to say no to drugs when the parents are 
saying yes," LaBouff said. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1992, LaBouff won a $550,000 grant from the U.S. Department of Education to 
spread that message in Hawthorne, Lawndale and Lennox. The three-year grant 
provides money for educational programs and helped stage last year's conference 
as well. The money also pays for a series of two-hour workshops at 6:30 p.m. on 
Thursdays. The meetings resume May 5 at Roosevelt Elementary School in 
Lawndale. 
</P>
</TEXT>
