<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: OXNARD; DEVELOPER GETS TAX BREAK ON FARMLAND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PHYLLIS W. JORDAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A developer hoping to turn strawberry fields into tract housing received a 
$107,000-a-year tax break from Ventura County this week, when a county panel 
agreed to tax the prime real estate at the same rate as farmland. 
</P>
<P>
 In a move that county officials fear could bring other developers forward 
demanding tax reductions, the county Assessment Appeals Board No. 1 slashed 
$10.7 million off the taxable value of 126 acres near Ormond Beach. 
</P>
<P>
 Oxnard Development Assn., which is planning a 3,500-home development on a site 
south of the Oxnard city limits, bought the three tracts in 1990 for prices 
ranging from $99,000 to $119,000 an acre. 
</P>
<P>
 The appeals panel, which includes county Supervisor John K. Flynn, agreed with 
the developer that the land -- still covered with strawberries -- should be 
valued at $30,000 an acre. 
</P>
<P>
 "Nobody pays $119,000 an acre for strawberry fields," said a skeptical James 
Dodd, tax specialist for the county assessor's office. 
</P>
<P>
 Dodd acknowledged that the recession has lowered property values, but argued 
that the land should still be worth $70,000 to $80,000 an acre. He cited 
similar prices in comparable land sales. 
</P>
<P>
 But the developer argued, and two of three panel members agreed, that the land 
should be taxed at agricultural levels until development is certain. 
</P>
<P>
 "None of these plans are certain, and in fact, one alternative presented was 
no development option," Richard Shapiro, a representative for the developer, 
told the board. "In other words, a zoning change is unpredictable." 
</P>
<P>
 Shapiro cited major hurdles, including an environmental impact review now 
under way, approval of annexation by Oxnard and "approval by an ever-changing 
City Council, with ever-changing political pressures and intentions." 
</P>
<P>
 Flynn said he found the arguments convincing, particularly in light of two 
court cases requiring the assessor to prove that the land will be developed "in 
the predictable future." "The assessor has a burden to carry," Flynn said. "The 
assessor has to be able to predict within a reasonable time frame." PHYLLIS W. 
JORDAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
